WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:01.420
Good afternoon, everybody,

2
00:00:03.740 --> 00:00:06.980
and welcome to this major symposium on human cancer models.

3
00:00:08.100 --> 00:00:11.820
It's my privilege to chair this session at the 2026

4
00:00:11.860 --> 00:00:12.460
ACR

5
00:00:13.480 --> 00:00:14.940
annual meeting.

6
00:00:15.840 --> 00:00:17.779
So precision oncology

7
00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:21.540
has fundamentally changed

8
00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:24.360
how we classify cancer.

9
00:00:25.700 --> 00:00:28.320
Through genomic and molecular profiling,

10
00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:33.260
we can now identify actionable alterations

11
00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:35.840
with unprecedented resolution,

12
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:39.200
and yet a critical gap remains.

13
00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:44.820
Tumors with similar genomic profiles often behave very

14
00:00:44.860 --> 00:00:46.480
differently in patients.

15
00:00:47.310 --> 00:00:49.820
They respond differently to therapy.

16
00:00:50.540 --> 00:00:51.200
They evolve

17
00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:53.180
under therapy

18
00:00:55.460 --> 00:00:59.420
and under therapy pressures. And so they develop resistance

19
00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:03.300
through mechanisms that still we probably don't fully

20
00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:04.080
understand,

21
00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:09.640
and that are not always predictable with genome sequencing

22
00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:11.200
alone.

23
00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:16.280
So this session actually is designed to

24
00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:20.160
discuss the translational relevance of human tumor

25
00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:24.040
systems, bridging discovery and validation with their

26
00:01:24.100 --> 00:01:26.300
clinical implementation to advance

27
00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:28.660
human cancer treatment.

28
00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:30.660
This symposium

29
00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:36.420
is built around a simple but consequential

30
00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:37.320
premise.

31
00:01:38.320 --> 00:01:41.900
To truly personalize cancer therapy, we must move

32
00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:45.820
beyond inference and toward direct measurements

33
00:01:46.180 --> 00:01:48.580
of therapeutic response in human tumor models.

34
00:01:49.960 --> 00:01:52.300
In other words, we must not only

35
00:01:53.860 --> 00:01:56.540
understand and ask what the tumor is,

36
00:01:57.380 --> 00:02:00.300
but what the tumor does when challenged with therapy.

37
00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:05.080
This shift from a descriptive to functional

38
00:02:05.120 --> 00:02:08.600
oncology represent a critical evolution

39
00:02:10.060 --> 00:02:13.120
in the diagnostic and treatment fields.

40
00:02:15.180 --> 00:02:18.420
Today's session is structured to reflect just this

41
00:02:19.580 --> 00:02:20.660
and this continuum.

42
00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:23.660
We will begin with Dr. David Tuveson,

43
00:02:24.580 --> 00:02:26.720
whose pioneering work in organoid models

44
00:02:27.540 --> 00:02:31.220
has advanced our ability to recapitulate tumor biology in solid

45
00:02:31.320 --> 00:02:33.680
cancer, such as

46
00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:36.520
pancreatic cancer.

47
00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:40.460
We will then hear from Jeffrey Tyner, Dr.

48
00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:44.320
Jeffrey Tyner, who will present on ex vivo functional testing

49
00:02:44.420 --> 00:02:45.100
approaches

50
00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:47.320
in leukemia.

51
00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:52.100
So we'll shift from solid tumors to liquid

52
00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:55.720
tumors, demonstrating how these models can directly inform

53
00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:00.260
therapeutic strategies. And finally, I will conclude with a

54
00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:03.600
perspective on functional precision oncology platform

55
00:03:04.280 --> 00:03:08.060
that is being translated into clinical decision-making

56
00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:10.380
using live patient tumor cells.

57
00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:17.090
Session goals are highlighting cutting-edge human tumor models,

58
00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:18.480
compare platforms

59
00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:23.280
and applications, discuss their potential integration into clinical

60
00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:27.300
workflows, and identify future direction,

61
00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:27.900
hopefully.

62
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.060
As you listen to this presentation, please,

63
00:03:31.940 --> 00:03:35.420
I will encourage you, the audience, to consider a few key

64
00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:39.340
questions that we have in mind and that will guide

65
00:03:39.420 --> 00:03:43.220
our discussion. What defines a truly predictive human cancer

66
00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:43.620
model?

67
00:03:45.200 --> 00:03:47.620
Where does genomic prediction fall short,

68
00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:49.040
and why?

69
00:03:50.340 --> 00:03:53.900
Can functional testing capture clinically relevant

70
00:03:54.240 --> 00:03:55.240
heterogeneity,

71
00:03:56.060 --> 00:03:58.160
including resistant subpopulations?

72
00:03:58.860 --> 00:04:02.820
And critically, what level of evidence do we need

73
00:04:02.860 --> 00:04:06.480
and is required to bring these approaches into routine clinical

74
00:04:06.549 --> 00:04:07.080
practice?

75
00:04:08.150 --> 00:04:10.840
The format is three speakers with 20 minutes each.

76
00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:15.320
Discussion after each talk is five minutes, and then we'll have a final panel

77
00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:17.340
discussion of 10 minutes.

78
00:04:18.601 --> 00:04:22.580
Dr. Tuveson will need to leave early today because he is

79
00:04:22.620 --> 00:04:26.550
engaged before the end of this session in another

80
00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:30.500
session here at the ACR. And for this reason, I encourage the

81
00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:34.100
audience to ask all the questions you guys want to ask to him

82
00:04:34.180 --> 00:04:37.120
directly in those five minutes, and later on you can email him.

83
00:04:38.380 --> 00:04:40.920
With that, it's my pleasure to introduce our first speaker.

84
00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:44.860
Please join me in welcoming Dr. David Tuveson.

85
00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:46.160
Thank you. Thank you,

86
00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:51.719
David.

87
00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:56.700
Thanks so much, Pierpaolo. That was very kind. Hello, everyone.

88
00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:00.170
We have about 20 seats, so you can get your

89
00:05:01.300 --> 00:05:05.040
standing calisthenics or you can sit down, but there's like 20 seats easily up

90
00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:05.260
here.

91
00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:07.680
So we've had this theme

92
00:05:09.020 --> 00:05:12.580
for about a decade to a decade and a half, and I've never seen this many people at

93
00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:14.420
an ACR conference interested in it.

94
00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:16.280
So it's great to see.

95
00:05:17.180 --> 00:05:20.680
The concept in the past is if you could build the model, it could be the

96
00:05:20.740 --> 00:05:24.300
avatar for your patient. It would be the bacteriology test.

97
00:05:24.380 --> 00:05:28.220
So you could multiplex your questions ex vivo, and then the doc

98
00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:31.780
could go in and actually go with the therapy that looks the best.

99
00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:34.320
That was the idea 15 years ago.

100
00:05:35.280 --> 00:05:37.420
I'll show you where we are in pancreas with that.

101
00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:41.760
So this slide has some photos. This is Amber,

102
00:05:41.960 --> 00:05:43.800
where my arrow is, and this is Granya.

103
00:05:44.469 --> 00:05:48.420
They were a pair on putting together a pancreas cancer trial looking at cytotoxic

104
00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:51.240
drugs in the era before the RAS drugs.

105
00:05:51.300 --> 00:05:54.580
So this started in 2018. And on the right are

106
00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:58.580
the same team with Jen Knox, who was the PI of the trial,

107
00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:02.510
Fayyaz Noota, who's a terrific quantitative biologist at

108
00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:06.216
Toronto, and Ken YiuAt

109
00:06:06.276 --> 00:06:08.476
Memorial, as well as Stephanie Ramotar.

110
00:06:09.136 --> 00:06:12.316
So I'm going to talk about an actual clinical trial we did with these models.

111
00:06:13.376 --> 00:06:17.016
This is my disclosure slide, which sadly is not going to be relevant for my talk.

112
00:06:18.576 --> 00:06:20.876
What's the hypothesis? I already told you.

113
00:06:21.156 --> 00:06:23.616
The hypothesis, this could be a bacteriology test.

114
00:06:23.676 --> 00:06:27.216
If you could stratify your patients with bad pancreas cancer,

115
00:06:27.436 --> 00:06:30.376
advanced, so a surgeon couldn't cut it out, would you help them?

116
00:06:31.236 --> 00:06:34.076
And this is, again, a question just using the cytotoxic regimens.

117
00:06:34.096 --> 00:06:36.816
There's two that are approved worldwide.

118
00:06:37.816 --> 00:06:41.736
And so the approach, again, was to develop the organoid models with a close

119
00:06:41.796 --> 00:06:43.866
collaboration and partnership with Hans Clevers from

120
00:06:44.696 --> 00:06:48.536
the Netherlands. You've all heard of him, and he was very generous and

121
00:06:48.636 --> 00:06:50.936
sent his senior scientists over to Cold Spring in

122
00:06:51.136 --> 00:06:54.876
2012 so that we could learn

123
00:06:54.956 --> 00:06:58.586
the Dutch methods, and then we innovated on it as

124
00:06:58.636 --> 00:07:02.026
Americans do, and developed ways to make

125
00:07:02.076 --> 00:07:04.556
organoids from mouse models and human specimens.

126
00:07:05.376 --> 00:07:07.556
And in the end of the day, the organoids were useful.

127
00:07:07.976 --> 00:07:11.706
They could model health, wild type cells,

128
00:07:12.136 --> 00:07:16.116
every stage of neoplasia, so early pre-invasive cancer, invasive

129
00:07:16.176 --> 00:07:17.316
cancer metastasis

130
00:07:18.276 --> 00:07:19.976
from the animal as well as from the human.

131
00:07:20.736 --> 00:07:22.816
And when you did the comparisons at the omics level,

132
00:07:24.036 --> 00:07:26.956
what you saw in the organoid was what you saw in the specimen.

133
00:07:27.416 --> 00:07:30.866
And so it looked good, like you could use it as a discovery

134
00:07:30.996 --> 00:07:34.196
platform and possibly as a therapeutic and diagnostic platform.

135
00:07:36.136 --> 00:07:37.616
So we decided to go

136
00:07:38.456 --> 00:07:41.196
into following our patients with such a method.

137
00:07:41.236 --> 00:07:42.476
This is a six-well dish

138
00:07:43.716 --> 00:07:47.016
with a human's hand holding it, and these little

139
00:07:47.756 --> 00:07:51.096
spots here are little drops of a extracellular matrix

140
00:07:51.376 --> 00:07:55.276
substrate. The common one we use is the commercial product known as Matrigel, but

141
00:07:55.316 --> 00:07:59.096
we've tested all kinds of them. And most of them

142
00:07:59.176 --> 00:08:02.616
work. They just vary in how you use them,

143
00:08:03.476 --> 00:08:04.336
the conditions,

144
00:08:05.536 --> 00:08:08.496
cost, et cetera. But lots of things will work.

145
00:08:08.556 --> 00:08:11.556
And again, this is just a cartoon, of course, of what an organoid looks like, a

146
00:08:12.896 --> 00:08:15.255
single cell layer in a cystic structure.

147
00:08:18.356 --> 00:08:22.276
And on the right are just some light field pictures of what you would

148
00:08:22.356 --> 00:08:25.936
see when they grow. It's always very exciting for people the first time they do it.

149
00:08:25.996 --> 00:08:27.276
It's kind of like a pet rock.

150
00:08:28.956 --> 00:08:32.557
So we use the organoids to ask questions about patients.

151
00:08:33.396 --> 00:08:36.256
So of course, we used it for discovery stuff in the mouse models, all of that.

152
00:08:36.876 --> 00:08:40.196
But in the human, we were asking, would the organoids tell us something that

153
00:08:40.516 --> 00:08:43.177
looked real, like it was occurring in the human?

154
00:08:44.116 --> 00:08:44.556
And so

155
00:08:45.696 --> 00:08:47.276
on the lower left, you see

156
00:08:48.256 --> 00:08:49.896
some therapeutic

157
00:08:51.496 --> 00:08:53.136
curves, some IC50 curves,

158
00:08:54.356 --> 00:08:58.286
where we were testing a variety of human-derived pancreas

159
00:08:58.356 --> 00:09:01.236
cancer organoids with gemcitabine, which is a monotherapeutic

160
00:09:01.816 --> 00:09:05.536
chemotherapy drug, which has been approved for several decades for pancreas.

161
00:09:06.056 --> 00:09:08.976
What I want you to appreciate is these curves are pretty tight.

162
00:09:09.356 --> 00:09:13.156
So there's about a tenfold window across dozens of

163
00:09:13.216 --> 00:09:16.416
samples. So the therapeutic index, if you were to compare a sensitive to a

164
00:09:16.456 --> 00:09:18.636
resistant patient, is pretty narrow.

165
00:09:19.956 --> 00:09:23.916
And here it's shown in tertiles where the most sensitive are on the bottom in

166
00:09:23.996 --> 00:09:25.636
blue and the most resistant in red.

167
00:09:26.416 --> 00:09:29.536
And we ask just very simple-minded questions with this data,

168
00:09:29.576 --> 00:09:33.436
like if the organoid showed sensitivity to these

169
00:09:33.456 --> 00:09:35.936
drugs, did the patient actually do well when they were treated?

170
00:09:36.216 --> 00:09:38.716
Anecdotally, it looked actually quite promising.

171
00:09:39.336 --> 00:09:42.776
We asked another question, which is, could you take super sensitive organoids

172
00:09:44.336 --> 00:09:48.306
and find transcriptional signatures that then you can apply to human samples

173
00:09:48.316 --> 00:09:50.056
and ask, could you stratify the patients?

174
00:09:51.056 --> 00:09:54.856
And such an approach is shown here, where in this case, patients that received

175
00:09:54.916 --> 00:09:57.156
FOLFIRINOX, a three-chemo drug regimen,

176
00:09:58.736 --> 00:10:00.776
we looked for an oxaliplatin signature.

177
00:10:00.796 --> 00:10:03.866
And in this case, if you had the signature, you were in blue, and you see basically

178
00:10:03.896 --> 00:10:07.556
more blue going down in this waterfall plot compared to the ones on the

179
00:10:07.576 --> 00:10:11.476
right. If you looked at overall survival, it wasn't

180
00:10:11.556 --> 00:10:15.176
that impressive. But again, this is a bad disease where people don't do well,

181
00:10:15.836 --> 00:10:18.516
and the drugs are helpful but not amazing.

182
00:10:19.316 --> 00:10:21.196
But this was the data that we had early on.

183
00:10:21.235 --> 00:10:24.856
And so it begged the question, could we get past this anecdotal

184
00:10:25.496 --> 00:10:28.956
retrospective approach and learn something on a bigger stage?

185
00:10:29.476 --> 00:10:32.816
And so with that in mind, we were able to start a collaboration with the University

186
00:10:32.856 --> 00:10:36.776
of Toronto. Stephen Gallinger is a surgeon there who had

187
00:10:36.796 --> 00:10:40.756
really amassed a large number of patient specimens where the molecular

188
00:10:40.776 --> 00:10:44.336
details of the patients were known following surgery by laser

189
00:10:44.436 --> 00:10:46.276
capture of the neoplastic cells.

190
00:10:47.596 --> 00:10:51.376
And Stephen and Jen Knox, who was the head medical oncologist there, was willing to

191
00:10:51.416 --> 00:10:55.406
collaborate across the northern border for us to put together

192
00:10:55.496 --> 00:10:58.176
a very large clinical study with four sites in the States.

193
00:10:58.956 --> 00:11:02.876
And the sites in the States were Hopkins, where Liz Jaffee was the co-PI with Jen

194
00:11:03.496 --> 00:11:07.156
on the trial, the Farber, where Brian Wolpin was the PI,

195
00:11:07.196 --> 00:11:08.336
Memorial, Ken Yu,

196
00:11:09.596 --> 00:11:13.236
and a very large healthcare system that we were able to work with at Long Island,

197
00:11:14.076 --> 00:11:15.796
Northwell Health, where Dan King was the PI.

198
00:11:17.216 --> 00:11:21.056
And so this very large collection of sites came

199
00:11:21.096 --> 00:11:24.716
together to do a randomized clinical trial comparing the two

200
00:11:24.796 --> 00:11:28.676
accepted cares for pancreas cancer, which were gemcitabine

201
00:11:28.736 --> 00:11:32.256
plus nab-paclitaxel, trade name Abraxane, with

202
00:11:32.296 --> 00:11:34.196
FOLFIRINOX, which is a three-chemo regimen.

203
00:11:35.156 --> 00:11:39.056
Randomized A versus B. We get the tissue to make organoids, and there's all kinds

204
00:11:39.096 --> 00:11:42.316
of other translational science. So this is what the trial looked

205
00:11:42.356 --> 00:11:45.576
like. Over 200 patients were

206
00:11:45.676 --> 00:11:49.436
screened. In the end, 160 were randomized, 80 assigned to each

207
00:11:49.516 --> 00:11:49.736
arm.

208
00:11:50.576 --> 00:11:53.596
When you do trials like this, when you have really sick patients, you lose patients

209
00:11:53.636 --> 00:11:57.436
because they unfortunately, the disease gallops through very

210
00:11:57.476 --> 00:12:01.236
rapidly. But in the end, we had 71 on the FOLFIRINOX arm and 69 on

211
00:12:01.276 --> 00:12:03.456
the gem/nab-paclitaxel arm.

212
00:12:04.736 --> 00:12:05.916
And again, it was a clinical study.

213
00:12:06.016 --> 00:12:09.724
They were comparing these two regimens.And we were doing the

214
00:12:09.764 --> 00:12:13.424
correlative science. And so this was the cohort demographics, because how

215
00:12:13.464 --> 00:12:17.404
medics present their trials, like when you do a randomized trial, are

216
00:12:17.444 --> 00:12:20.104
they truly random, the populations, in terms of gender,

217
00:12:21.764 --> 00:12:25.744
amount of disease, their ECOG performance status, meaning how healthy or sick

218
00:12:25.804 --> 00:12:28.884
are they? What is their ethnicity and ancestry?

219
00:12:30.084 --> 00:12:33.924
And what was the final diagnosis? Was it adenocarcinoma versus

220
00:12:34.024 --> 00:12:34.524
other things?

221
00:12:35.604 --> 00:12:39.484
There's a blood biomarker in pancreas, which is a glycan called CA19-9.

222
00:12:40.504 --> 00:12:44.424
And then, of course, metastatic burden, RAS mutational status,

223
00:12:44.484 --> 00:12:44.964
et cetera.

224
00:12:45.864 --> 00:12:48.444
More or less, they were pretty well-matched, although there were some

225
00:12:49.344 --> 00:12:50.764
caveats shown here.

226
00:12:52.204 --> 00:12:56.124
These were patients, again, never treated, no operations, no other treatment

227
00:12:56.164 --> 00:12:59.564
beforehand. So this was the clinical result, and the clinical result was

228
00:12:59.604 --> 00:13:03.564
interesting to those of us who are pancreas cancer med-oncs, in that

229
00:13:03.624 --> 00:13:07.604
the gemcitabine plus the fancy Taxol did better than the three-drug

230
00:13:07.684 --> 00:13:11.614
regimen, which was developed by our colleagues in France and was thought to be the

231
00:13:11.684 --> 00:13:14.464
"more active, more strong approach."

232
00:13:16.044 --> 00:13:19.394
And so that wasn't the case in a randomized trial in overall survival.

233
00:13:19.394 --> 00:13:23.064
And if you looked at the subtypes of pancreas, as is true of

234
00:13:23.144 --> 00:13:26.864
every cancer, there are differences of the cancer.

235
00:13:27.024 --> 00:13:29.004
Pierpaolo talked about heterogeneity.

236
00:13:29.724 --> 00:13:32.944
So there are heterogeneity across patients as well as within a patient.

237
00:13:33.414 --> 00:13:37.284
And so heterogeneity across patients in pancreas, there's classical and there's

238
00:13:37.324 --> 00:13:37.704
basal.

239
00:13:38.524 --> 00:13:38.844
And that's a

240
00:13:41.224 --> 00:13:43.664
simplification, and I'll talk about that in a bit, too.

241
00:13:44.224 --> 00:13:47.624
But essentially, the patients with basal, which is more mesenchymal, did worse,

242
00:13:47.824 --> 00:13:50.964
particularly when they got FOLFIRINOX, and the patients with classical, when they

243
00:13:50.984 --> 00:13:53.703
got gem plus the Taxol, did better.

244
00:13:55.784 --> 00:13:58.684
And this was, again, a different way to look at that same data.

245
00:13:59.904 --> 00:14:03.724
And so the blood biomarker that physicians use in their clinic is this

246
00:14:03.744 --> 00:14:07.574
glycan I talked about. It's actually a pretty fascinating molecule, and

247
00:14:07.624 --> 00:14:11.294
if it tails down fast within a few weeks, the patient's going to do

248
00:14:11.324 --> 00:14:13.904
well. If it does the opposite, patient's not going to do well.

249
00:14:13.944 --> 00:14:17.004
That's sort of a clinical observation in the past, and this study really confirmed

250
00:14:17.084 --> 00:14:20.944
that. For those patients where it tailed down, they were in blue, they actually

